Key Findings

Trend Analysis
AAPL stock prices show a strong upward trend over the 10-year period.

Linear Regression Model

Price_t = -7.492 + 2.112 × t

Interpretation:

Average increase ≈ $2.11 per month
Adjusted R² ≈ 0.9446

This indicates that approximately 94% of the variation in AAPL prices is explained by the time trend.

Non-Stationarity

The original price series exhibited:

Slowly decaying ACF
Increasing block mean
Increasing block variance

These are typical properties of non-stationary financial time series.

Stationarity Transformation

Stationarity was achieved through:

Log transformation
First-order differencing

After transformation:

Mean became approximately constant
Variance stabilized
ACF displayed white-noise behavior.

Autoregressive Models

AR(1)

y_t = 0.01655 + 0.2184 y_{t-1}

Adjusted R² ≈ 0.0407

AR(2)

y_t = 0.01773 + 0.2478 y_{t-1} − 0.0998 y_{t-2}

The second lag was not statistically significant, so AR(1) was preferred as the more parsimonious model.

Structural Break

A large spike appears in the transformed series during 2020, corresponding to the global financial shock during the COVID-19 pandemic. This represents a structural break caused by an external real-world event rather than a statistical artifact.

Conclusions

The transformed AAPL series behaves close to a log-normal random walk. This implies that past price changes have limited predictive power, which is consistent with the weak form of the Efficient Market Hypothesis for highly liquid stocks.

